		<p style="margin:0pt;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;line-height:100%;text-align:center;font-family:Times New Roman;font-weight:bold;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">THE FIRST OF LONG ISLAND CORPORATION</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;line-height:100%;text-align:center;font-family:Times New Roman;font-weight:bold;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">10 Glen Head Road</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;line-height:100%;text-align:center;font-family:Calibri;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-weight:bold;font-size:10pt;">Glen Head, New York 11545</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;line-height:100%;text-align:center;font-family:Calibri;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-weight:bold;font-size:10pt;">(516) 671-4900</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;line-height:100%;text-align:center;font-family:Calibri;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-weight:bold;font-size:10pt;">&#xFEFF;</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;line-height:200%;text-align:center;font-family:Calibri;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-weight:bold;font-size:10pt;">PROXY STATEMENT</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;line-height:200%;text-align:center;font-family:Calibri;font-size: 10pt">
			<a name="InformationAboutAnnualMeetingofStckhldrs"></a><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-weight:bold;font-size:10pt;">INFORMATION ABOUT THE ANNUAL MEETING OF STOCKHOLDERS</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Calibri;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">The </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">accompanying proxy is being solicited by the Board of Directors (&#x201C;Board&#x201D;) of The First of Long Island Corporation (&#x201C;Corporation&#x201D; or &#x201C;Company&#x201D;) for use at the Annual Meeting of Stockholders to be held at 10:00 A.M. local time at The Mansion at Oyster Bay, One Southwoods Road, Woodbury, New York on April 21, 2020.&nbsp;&nbsp;The approximate date on which proxy statements and forms of proxy are first being sent or given to </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">stockholders is March 20, 2020</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">.</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Calibri;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">Proxies </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">in the accompanying form that are properly executed and duly returned to the Corporation, or voted electronically, will be voted at the meeting </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">in accordance with the instructions provided.&nbsp;&nbsp;Where no instructions are indicated, </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">properly</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;"> executed proxies will be voted &#x201C;For&#x201D; the proposals set forth in this proxy statement.&nbsp; </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">Each proxy granted may be revoked at any time prior to its exercise by written notice filed with the secretary of the Corporation, by the submission of a later dated and executed proxy or by notice given during the meeting by the stockholder to the presiding officer of the meeting.&nbsp;&nbsp;The presence in person or by proxy of the holders of a majority of the shares entitled to vote at the annual meeting constitutes a quorum for the transaction of business.&nbsp;&nbsp;The meeting (whether or not a quorum is present) may be adjourned to a subsequent date, provided notice of the time and place to which the meeting is adjourned are announced at the meeting at which the adjournment is taken.&nbsp;&nbsp;At an adjourned meeting, any business may be transacted which might have been transacted at the meeting as originally scheduled.&nbsp; </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;color:#000000;font-size:10pt;">In the event there are not sufficient votes for a quorum, or to approve or ratify any matter being presented at the time of this Annual Meeting, the Annual Meeting may be adjourned in order to permit the further solicitation of proxies</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;color:#000000;font-size:10pt;">.</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:center;font-family:Calibri;font-size: 10pt">
			<a name="VotingSecuritiesandPrincipalStckhldrs"></a><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-weight:bold;font-size:10pt;">VOTING SECURITIES AND PRINCIPAL STOCKHOLDERS</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Calibri;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">The </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">only class of voting securities of the Corporation is its Common Stock, $.10 par value ("Common Stock"), each share of which entitles the holder thereof to one vote except in the election of directors, where votes may be cumulated as described herein.&nbsp;&nbsp;Only stockholders of record at the close of business on March 6, 2020 are entitled to notice of and to vote at the meeting</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">.</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Calibri;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">As </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">of March 6, 2020, there </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">were 23,793,128 shares of the</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;"> Common Stock issued, all of which were outstanding and entitled to vote.&nbsp; </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">Based on information available</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">, the only persons owning beneficially more than five percent (5%) of the Common Stock of the Corporation as of March 6, 2020 are identified in the table below</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">. &nbsp;</font>
		</p>

		</td><td style="width:0pt;"><p style="width:0pt;width:0pt;font-size:0pt;"></p></td><td align="left" valign="top">
			<p style="line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Calibri;font-size: 10pt;margin:0pt;">
			<font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;color:#000000;">Includes </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;color:#000000;">3</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;color:#000000;">2</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;color:#000000;">,</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;color:#000000;">169</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;color:#000000;"> shares that can be acquired by the exercise of stock options</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;color:#000000;">.</font></p></td></tr></table></div>
		<p style="margin:6pt 0pt;line-height:100%;text-align:center;font-family:Calibri;font-size: 10pt">
			<a name="VotingProcedures"></a><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-weight:bold;font-size:10pt;color:#000000;">VOTING PROCEDURES AND METHODS OF COUNTING VOTES</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Calibri;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;color:#000000;">As </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;color:#000000;">to </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;color:#000000;">Proposal 1 regarding the election of directors, the proxy card being provided by the Board enables a stockholder to vote &#x201C;For&#x201D; the election of the seven nominees proposed by the Board or to &#x201C;Withhold Authority&#x201D; to vote for the nominees being proposed.&nbsp;&nbsp;As discussed under Proposal 1, cumulative voting applies to the election of directors.&nbsp;&nbsp;Directors are elected by a plurality of the votes cast, without regard to either broker non-votes or proxies as to which the authority to vote for the nominee is withheld</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;color:#000000;">.</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Calibri;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;color:#000000;">As </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;color:#000000;">to </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;color:#000000;">Proposals 2 and 3, a stockholder may: (1) vote &#x201C;For&#x201D; the item, (2) vote &#x201C;Against&#x201D; the item, or (3) &#x201C;Abstain&#x201D; from voting on the item.&nbsp;&nbsp;In order to approve Proposals 2 and 3, each proposal must receive the affirmative vote of a majority of the shares voting on each matter at the annual meeting without regard to either shares as to which the &#x201C;Abstain&#x201D; box is marked or broker non-votes</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;color:#000000;">.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Calibri;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;color:#000000;">Proxies </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;color:#000000;">solicited hereby will be returned to the Corporation, tabulated by the Corporation&#x2019;s registrar and transfer agent and reviewed by the inspectors of election designated by the Board</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;color:#000000;">.</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-weight:bold;font-size:10pt;color:#000000;">&nbsp;</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt;font-family:Calibri;line-height:115%;font-size: 10pt">

		</p>
		<p><font size="1"> </font></p><div style="width:100%">

		<p style="margin:0pt;text-align:center;line-height:100%;font-family:Calibri;font-size: 10pt">

			<font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;"></font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">2</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;"></font>

		</p>

		<p style="margin:0pt;text-align:center;line-height:100%;font-family:Calibri;font-size: 11pt">

			&nbsp;

		</p>

</div><hr size="3" style="color:#999999" width="100%" align="center"></hr><p style="page-break-after:always">&nbsp;</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt;font-family:Calibri;line-height:115%;;font-size: 10pt"><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-weight:bold;font-size:10pt;"></font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:center;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Calibri;font-size: 10pt">
			<a name="Proposal1ElectionofDirectors"></a><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-weight:bold;font-size:10pt;">PROPOSAL 1</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:center;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Calibri;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-weight:bold;font-size:10pt;">ELECTION OF DIRECTORS</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-weight:bold;font-size:10pt;"> FOR </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-weight:bold;font-size:10pt;">ONE OR </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-weight:bold;font-size:10pt;">TWO YEAR TERMS</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Calibri;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">The </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">Board of the Corporation currently consists of thirteen members.&nbsp;&nbsp;Effective as of the Annual Meeting, Michael N. Vittorio, former President and CEO of the Corporation, will discontinue his service as a Class I director following his retirement on December 31, 2019 and in accordance with the terms of his employment agreement.&nbsp;&nbsp;The Board has nominated Paul T. Canarick, Alexander L. Cover, Stephen V. Murphy, Peter Quick, Denise Strain and Eric J. Tveter for re-election as Class II directors to serve two year terms and Christopher Becker for election as Class I director to serve a one year term that is coterminous with other Class I directors.&nbsp;&nbsp;Each </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">continuing </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">Board member and nominee, with the exception of Christopher Becker who serves as President and Chief Executive Officer (&#x201C;CEO&#x201D;) of the Corporation and its wholly owned bank subsidiary, The First National Bank of Long Island (&#x201C;Bank&#x201D;), is independent as defined in the Nasdaq Rules</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Calibri;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">The Board is divided into two classes, Class I and Class II.&nbsp;&nbsp;The following table sets forth the present composition of the Board</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">.</font>
		</p>

		<p style="margin:12pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Calibri;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">As </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">to the election of directors, each stockholder entitled to vote has the right to vote, in person or by proxy, the number of shares owned by him or her for as many persons as there are directors to be elected.&nbsp;&nbsp;A stockholder may also cumulate his or her votes by giving one candidate as many votes as the number of directors to be elected multiplied by the number of his or her shares or by evenly distributing such votes on the same principle among any number of candidates.&nbsp;&nbsp;Cumulative voting can affect the election of directors if there are more nominees for director than positions to be filled.&nbsp;&nbsp;In the event that cumulative voting is in effect, it is the intention of the proxies to vote cumulatively for the nominees listed, and if authority for any nominee or nominees is withheld, the votes will be distributed among the remaining candidates at the discretion of the Board</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">.</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Calibri;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">It </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">is intended that shares represented by properly executed proxies will be voted at the meeting in accordance with the instructions indicated thereon and, in the absence of contrary indication, for the re-election of directors Canarick, Cover, Murphy, Quick, Strain and Tveter and for the election of director Becker.&nbsp;&nbsp;Each of the </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">nominees for </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">Class I and II directors will hold office until his or her successor is elected and qualified.&nbsp;&nbsp;If at the time of the 2020 Annual Meeting any of the nominees named above is unavailable or chooses not to serve as a director (an event that the Board does not now anticipate), the proxies will be voted for the election as director of such other person or persons as the Board may designate</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">.</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt;line-height:100%;text-align:center;font-family:Calibri;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-weight:bold;font-size:10pt;">The Board of Directors recommends a vote FOR all named nominees.</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:6pt 0pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Calibri;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">The </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">following table sets forth a brief description of the business experience during the past five years of each of the nominees and Board members continuing in office.&nbsp;&nbsp;It also indicates any other directorships held during the past five years in any company with a class of securities registered pursuant to section 12 of the Securities Exchange Act of 1934 (&#x201C;1934 Act&#x201D;) or subject to the requirements of section 15(d) of the 1934 Act or any company registered as an investment company under the Investment Company Act of 1940.&nbsp;&nbsp;The year set forth for each director is the year in which the person named became a director of the Corporation and the Bank with the exception of Mr. Hogan, who became a director of the Corporation upon its formation in 1984</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">.</font>
		</p>

		<p style="margin:6pt 0pt;line-height:100%;text-align:center;font-family:Calibri;font-size: 10pt">
			<a name="QualificationsofDirectors"></a><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-weight:bold;font-size:10pt;">QUALIFICATIONS OF DIRECTORS</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-indent:18pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Calibri;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-weight:bold;font-size:10pt;;font-size: 10pt;font-family:Calibri;text-indent:0pt;margin-left:0pt;padding:0pt 18pt 0pt 0pt;"></font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;font-size:10pt;">Diversity</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-weight:bold;font-size:10pt;">.&nbsp; </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">The </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">Governance and Nominating Committee believes that the Board as a whole should adequately reflect the diversity of the Company&#x2019;s constituencies and the communities in which the Company conducts business.&nbsp;&nbsp;Although the Committee considers diversity in identifying nominees for director, it does not have a formal policy in this regard.&nbsp;&nbsp;The Committee has a broad view of diversity, and conceptualizes it to include differences of viewpoint, professional experience, education, skill and other individual qualities and attributes that contribute to board heterogeneity, as well as race, ethnicity, gender, and other characteristics</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">. &nbsp;</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-indent:18pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Calibri;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;;font-size: 10pt;font-family:Calibri;text-indent:0pt;margin-left:0pt;padding:0pt 18pt 0pt 0pt;"></font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;font-size:10pt;">Specific Core Competencies</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-weight:bold;font-size:10pt;">.&nbsp; </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">In </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">addition to general qualifications and the consideration of diversity, the Governance and Nominating Committee has developed a Skill Sets Matrix that sets forth the specific core competencies it believes one or more Board members should possess.&nbsp;&nbsp;The matrix is used to evaluate the collective skills of the existing Board and identify the skills that the Committee should seek when filling a Board vacancy or increasing the size of the Board.&nbsp;&nbsp;The Governance and Nominating Committee recognizes that some Board members may possess many of the core competencies, while others will possess only a few, but that each Board member should have particular strength with respect to at least one.&nbsp;&nbsp;The identified core competencies, which are</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">&nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">subject to change from time to time, include, but are not limited to: corporate governance, banking, strategic planning, business leadership, organizational management and/or business operations, accounting and reporting, finance and/or investments, technology and/or </font>
		</p>
		<p><font size="1"> </font></p><div style="width:100%">

		<p style="margin:0pt;text-align:center;line-height:100%;font-family:Calibri;font-size: 10pt">

			<font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;"></font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">4</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;"></font>

		</p>

		<p style="margin:0pt;text-align:center;line-height:100%;font-family:Calibri;font-size: 11pt">

			&nbsp;

		</p>

</div><hr size="3" style="color:#999999" width="100%" align="center"></hr><p style="page-break-after:always">&nbsp;</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Calibri;font-size: 10pt"><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">information security, mergers and acquisitions, legal and/or regulatory, real estate, marketing and/or public relations and financial accounting experience necessary to qualify as an &#x201C;audit committee financial expert&#x201D; as defined in Regulation S-K of the Securities and Exchange Commission (&#x201C;SEC&#x201D;).</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Calibri;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">With </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">respect to each of the </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">Corporation</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">&#x2019;s directors, the narrative that follows sets forth the specific experience, qualifications, attributes and skills that led to the conclusion that the person should serve as a director considering the Company&#x2019;s business and structure and the general qualifications and core competencies identified and deemed desirable by the Governance and Nominating Committee</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">.&nbsp; </font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-indent:18pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Calibri;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-weight:bold;font-size:10pt;">Christopher Becker - </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">Mr. </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">Becker joined the Board in January 2020 upon being named President and Chief Executive Officer of the Corporation and the Bank.&nbsp;&nbsp;Mr. Becker has been employed by the Bank since 2011 most recently serving as Executive Vice President and Chief Risk Officer of the Corporation and the Bank and Corporate Secretary of the Corporation.&nbsp;&nbsp;For the past nine years, Mr. Becker has been responsible for the Bank&#x2019;s enterprise risk management program including oversight of strategic planning, technology, loan and deposit operations, compliance, administration of internal audit, facilities and certain credit administration functions.&nbsp;&nbsp;Prior to joining the Bank, Mr. Becker served as Executive Vice President and Chief Financial Officer at the Bank of Smithtown and previously as Director, President and Chief Executive Officer of a national bank in organization.&nbsp;&nbsp;Mr. Becker began his career at Bridgehampton National Bank and served ultimately as Executive Vice President and Chief Operating Officer.&nbsp;&nbsp;Mr. Becker&#x2019;s experience has provided him with a number of core competencies identified by the Governance and Nominating Committee, which include corporate governance, banking, strategic planning, business leadership, organizational management and business operations, accounting and reporting, finance and investments, technology and information security, mergers and acquisitions, legal and regulatory, real estate and marketing and public relations</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">.</font>
		</p>

		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-indent:18pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Calibri;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-weight:bold;font-size:10pt;">Walter C. Teagle III -</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">&nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">Mr. </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">Teagle joined the Board in 1996, became Chairman of the Board in 2005 and is an ex officio member for all purposes of all Board committees of the Corporation and the Bank.&nbsp;&nbsp;Mr. Teagle is currently President and owner of Teagle Management, Inc., a private investment firm, Chairman and Director of The Teagle Foundation, Inc. and Managing General Partner of Gulo Capital Partners L.P., a private investment partnership.&nbsp;&nbsp;Mr. Teagle&#x2019;s past experience includes a variety of executive and board positions including Managing Director, Groton Partners LLC, a merchant banking firm; Officer and Managing Director, Groton Asset Management LLC, an investment management company; Executive Vice President and Director, Lexent, Inc., a publicly-held infrastructure service provider; and President, Chief Executive Officer, and Director, Metro Design Systems, Inc., an engineering design services firm.&nbsp;&nbsp;Mr. Teagle has also been a director of not-for-profit entities.&nbsp;&nbsp;Mr. Teagle&#x2019;s experience has provided him with a number of the core competencies identified by the Governance and Nominating Committee, which include corporate governance, banking, strategic planning, business leadership, organizational management and business operations, finance and investments, technology and information security, and mergers and acquisitions</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">. &nbsp;</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-indent:18pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Calibri;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-weight:bold;font-size:10pt;">Eric J. Tveter -</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">&nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">Mr. </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">Tveter joined the Board in 2013 and is Chairman of the Compensation Committee.&nbsp;&nbsp;He is currently Chairman of ETC Ventures LLC and Veloce Esports Limited. He is formerly Chairman of Upc Switzerland and Chief Executive Officer of Upc Central Europe</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;"> Group</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">, Liberty Global plc.&nbsp;&nbsp;Prior to that he was Chief Executive Officer, Central Europe Group, Liberty Global plc</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">.&nbsp; </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">Mr. Tveter has extensive knowledge and experience in the US, UK and European cable industries.&nbsp;&nbsp;Mr. Tveter&#x2019;s experience has provided him with a number of the core competencies identified by the Governance and Nominating Committee, which include corporate governance, banking, strategic planning, business leadership, organizational management and business operations, accounting and reporting, finance, technology and information security, mergers and acquisitions, legal and regulatory, real estate, marketing and public relations</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">. &nbsp;</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt;font-family:Calibri;line-height:115%;font-size: 10pt">

		</p>
		<p><font size="1"> </font></p><div style="width:100%">

		<p style="margin:0pt;text-align:center;line-height:100%;font-family:Calibri;font-size: 10pt">

			<font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;"></font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">6</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;"></font>

		</p>

		<p style="margin:0pt;text-align:center;line-height:100%;font-family:Calibri;font-size: 11pt">

			&nbsp;

		</p>

</div><hr size="3" style="color:#999999" width="100%" align="center"></hr><p style="page-break-after:always">&nbsp;</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt;font-family:Calibri;line-height:115%;;font-size: 10pt"><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;"></font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:center;font-family:Calibri;font-size: 10pt">
			<a name="BoardLeadership"></a><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-weight:bold;font-size:10pt;">BOARD LEADERSHIP STRUCTURE</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Calibri;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">The </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">Board has determined that the Chairman of the Board will be an independent director.&nbsp;&nbsp;The Board believes that stockholder interests are best served by having a Chairman of the Board who is independent of management and whose exclusive responsibility is the long-term best interest of the Corporation&#x2019;s stockholders</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">.</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Calibri;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">Walter </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">C. </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">Teagle III has served as Chairman of the Board since May 2005.&nbsp;&nbsp;As Chairman, Mr. Teagle organizes the work of the Board and ensures that the Board has access to sufficient information to enable it to carry out its functions, including monitoring the Corporation&#x2019;s performance and the performance of the Board and management.&nbsp;&nbsp;The role of the Chairman of the Board includes: (1) presiding over all meetings of the Board and stockholders, including regular executive sessions of the Board in which the CEO, a management director, and other members of management do not participate; (2) establishing the annual agenda of the Board and agendas of each meeting in consultation with the CEO; (3) serving as an ex officio member of each </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">B</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">oard committee and advising with respect to the work of each Board committee; (4) coordinating periodic Board reviews of management&#x2019;s strategic plan for the Corporation; and (5) coordinating the Compensation Committee annual performance review of the CEO</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">.</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:center;font-family:Calibri;font-size: 1pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-weight:bold;font-size:1pt;">&#xFEFF;</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:center;font-family:Calibri;font-size: 10pt">
			<a name="BoardRoleinRiskOversight"></a><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-weight:bold;font-size:10pt;">BOARD&#x2019;S ROLE IN RISK OVERSIGHT</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Calibri;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">Risk </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">is an integral part of Board and Board committee discussions.&nbsp;&nbsp;The significant risks facing the Corporation are set forth in an Enterprise Risk Management document.&nbsp;&nbsp;The Corporation&#x2019;s management team, which includes a Chief Risk Officer, is responsible for identifying, assessing and managing risk and the Board is responsible for risk oversight and fulfills this responsibility primarily through its committees.&nbsp;&nbsp;In granting authority to management, approving policies and strategies and receiving management reports, the Board and its committees consider, among other things, the risks that the Corporation faces.&nbsp;&nbsp;For each critical risk, such as credit risk, interest rate risk, liquidity risk, and cybersecurity risk, the Corporation has a formal written policy that is approved by an appropriate Board committee or the full Board</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">.</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Calibri;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">As </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">reflected in the Corporation&#x2019;s Corporate Governance Guidelines, the Board and its committees address succession planning risk both in the ordinary course of business and on a contingent basis in case of unexpected events.&nbsp;&nbsp;The Corporation has comprehensive written succession planning documents that cover the Board and its committees, the CEO and the other members of executive management and from time to time retains consultants with expertise in succession planning matters.&nbsp;&nbsp;The Corporation&#x2019;s succession planning documents are updated no less often than annually and are actively used by the Board and its committees to oversee and ensure a smooth transition should Board members or key members of executive management retire or otherwise leave the employ of the Corporation</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">.</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Calibri;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">The following table sets forth the risk oversight responsibilities</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;"> of the Board and Board committees</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">.</font>
		</p>
		<div style="width:100%"><table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" align="center" style="border-collapse:collapse;width: 100.00%;line-height:100%;margin-bottom:0pt;margin-left:0pt;">

					<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Calibri;line-height:115%;height:1.00pt;overflow:hidden;font-size: 1pt">
						<font style="display: inline;font-size:1pt;">&#xFEFF;</font></p>
				</td>
				<td valign="bottom" style="width:50.98%;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-left:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-right:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;height:1.00pt;padding:0pt 6.5pt">
					<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Calibri;line-height:115%;height:1.00pt;overflow:hidden;font-size:0pt;">
						&nbsp;</p>
				</td>
			</tr>
			<tr>
				<td valign="bottom" style="border-right:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-left:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;width:49.02%;padding:0pt 6.5pt">
					<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;font-family:Calibri;line-height:115%;font-size: 10pt">
						<font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-weight:bold;font-size:10pt;text-decoration:underline;">Board or Board Committee</font></p>
				</td>
				<td valign="bottom" style="border-left:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-right:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;width:50.98%;padding:0pt 6.5pt">

				</td>

				</td>

					<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;font-family:Calibri;line-height:115%;font-size: 10pt">
						<font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">Credit and Allowance for </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">Credit</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;"> Losses</font></p>
				</td>

		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Calibri;font-size: 1pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-weight:bold;font-size:1pt;">&#xFEFF;</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Calibri;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-weight:bold;font-size:10pt;">CEO Succession</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">.</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;font-size:10pt;"> &nbsp; &nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">On </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">January 1, 2020 Christopher Becker succeeded Michael N. Vittorio as President and CEO of the Corporation and the Bank following Mr. Vittorio&#x2019;s retirement on December 31, 2019.&nbsp;&nbsp;In accordance with the terms of his employment agreement, Mr. Vittorio is expected to continue his service as a director until the annual meeting of stockholders on April 21, 2020.&nbsp;&nbsp;The succession was originally announced on March 19, 2019 and Messrs. Becker and Vittorio worked together throughout the remainder of 2019 to assure a smooth transition</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">.</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:center;font-family:Calibri;font-size: 10pt">
			<a name="MeetingsofBOD"></a><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-weight:bold;font-size:10pt;">MEETINGS OF THE BOARD OF DIRECTORS</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Calibri;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">All </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">of the members of the Board of the Corporation also serve on the Board of the Bank.&nbsp;&nbsp;The Board of the Corporation held ten regular meetings and one special meeting during 2019.&nbsp;&nbsp;Each director attended at least 75% of the aggregate number of Board meetings and meetings of the committees on which such director served.&nbsp;&nbsp;The Board meets regularly in executive session throughout the year</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">.</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">&nbsp;</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:center;font-family:Calibri;font-size: 10pt">
			<a name="BoardCommitteeMeetings"></a><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-weight:bold;font-size:10pt;">BOARD COMMITTEES AND MEETINGS</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Calibri;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">The </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">Board of the Corporation has three standing committees: the Governance and Nominating Committee; the Audit Committee; and the Compensation Committee.&nbsp;&nbsp;The Board of the Bank also has two standing committees: the Loan Committee and the Asset Liability Committee</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">.&nbsp; </font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Calibri;font-size: 10pt">

		</p>
		<p><font size="1"> </font></p><div style="width:100%">

		<p style="margin:0pt;text-align:center;line-height:100%;font-family:Calibri;font-size: 10pt">

			<font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;"></font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">7</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;"></font>

		</p>

		<p style="margin:0pt;text-align:center;line-height:100%;font-family:Calibri;font-size: 11pt">

			&nbsp;

		</p>

</div><hr size="3" style="color:#999999" width="100%" align="center"></hr><p style="page-break-after:always">&nbsp;</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Calibri;;font-size: 10pt"><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-weight:bold;font-size:10pt;">Governance and Nominating Committee</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Calibri;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">All </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">the members of the Corporation&#x2019;s Governance and Nominating Committee are independent directors as defined in the Nasdaq Rules.&nbsp;&nbsp;The members of the Governance and Nominating Committee are Paul T. Canarick, Alexander L. Cover, Howard Thomas Hogan, Jr., Peter Quick</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;color:#000000;font-size:10pt;">, Denise Strain, </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">Milbrey Rennie Taylor and Walter C. Teagle III.&nbsp;&nbsp;The Committee met four times during 2019</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">.</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Calibri;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">The </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">Corporation&#x2019;s Board has adopted a formal written charter for the Governance and Nominating Committee.&nbsp;&nbsp;A current copy of the charter and the Corporation&#x2019;s Corporate Governance Guidelines are available on the Corporation&#x2019;s website by going to </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">www.FNBLI.com</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">, &nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">placing the cursor over &#x201C;Investor Relations,&#x201D; then clicking on &#x201C;Corporate Governance&#x201D; and then clicking on &#x201C;Board Governance and Nominating Committee Charter&#x201D; or &#x201C;Corporate Governance Guidelines</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">.&#x201D;</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Calibri;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">Among </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">other things, the Governance and Nominating Committee is currently responsible for: (1) maintaining the director succession plan; (2) identifying individuals qualified to become Board members and recommending to the Board the director nominees for the next annual meeting of stockholders; (3) </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">recommending to the Board written corporate governance guidelines and monitoring compliance with said guidelines; (4) leading the Board in an annual Board self-assessment and reporting to the Board on its own self-assessment and the self-assessments performed by the other Board committees; (5) recommending to the Board director candidates for each committee; and (6) establishing the director skill sets matrix to evaluate the collective skills of the existing </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">B</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">oard and to identify skills that may be sought when filling vacancies</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">.</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Calibri;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">Although </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">the Corporation has a long history of being able to attract and maintain a cohesive Board with the variety of skills necessary to oversee the affairs of the Corporation, the Governance and Nominating Committee will consider director candidates recommended by stockholders.&nbsp;&nbsp;Submission of candidates may be made in writing at any time.&nbsp;&nbsp;However, to be considered by the Governance and </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">Nominating Committee for nomination at the 2021 annual meeting, such submissions should be made no </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">later than December 10, 2020</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;"> to the Chair of the Governance and Nominating Committee at the Corporation&#x2019;s address set forth in this proxy statement.&nbsp;&nbsp;In addition, nominations for the election of directors may be made by any stockholder entitled to vote for the election of directors provided that such nominations are made in accordance with the provisions of the Corporation&#x2019;s bylaws establishing the information and notice requirements for such nominations</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">. &nbsp;</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Calibri;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">In </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">addition to interviews, the Governance and Nominating Committee may evaluate potential nominees by reviewing resumes, checking business and/or personal references, and performing background checks as deemed appropriate.&nbsp;&nbsp;The Corporation has not paid a fee to any third party or parties to assist in identifying or evaluating potential nominees</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">.</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Calibri;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">Except </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">for Mr. Becker, all of the nominees approved by the Governance and Nominating Committee for inclusion on the Corporation&#x2019;s proxy card for the Annual Meeting of Stockholders to be held April 21, 2020 are Class II directors standing for re-election.&nbsp;&nbsp;Mr. Becker was appointed by the Board effective January 1, 2020 upon being named President and CEO of the Corporation. Mr. Becker stands for election as a Class I director to serve a one year term that is coterminous with other Class I directors</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">.</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Calibri;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-weight:bold;font-size:10pt;">Audit Committee</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Calibri;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">The </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">members of the Audit Committee are Alexander L. Cover, </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;color:#000000;font-size:10pt;">John J. Desmond, </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">Peter Quick and Walter C. Teagle III.&nbsp;&nbsp;The Committee met eight times during 2019</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">.</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Calibri;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">The </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">Corporation&#x2019;s Board has adopted a formal written charter for the Audit Committee.&nbsp;&nbsp;A current copy of the charter is available on the Corporation&#x2019;s website by going to </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">www.FNBLI.com</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">, &nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">placing the cursor over &#x201C;Investor Relations,&#x201D; then clicking on &#x201C;Corporate Governance&#x201D; and then clicking on &#x201C;Board Audit Committee Charter</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">.&#x201D;</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:100%;font-family:Calibri;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">The</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">&nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">Board has determined that all members of the Audit Committee are independent as independence for audit committee members is defined in SEC Rule 10A-3 and the Nasdaq Rules.&nbsp;&nbsp;The Board has also determined that Alexander L. Cover and John J. Desmond each qualify as an &#x201C;audit committee financial expert&#x201D; as that term is defined in Item 407 of Regulation S-K of the Securities and Exchange Commission.&nbsp;&nbsp;The Board has also determined that all members of the Audit Committee have banking or related financial management expertise</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">.</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Calibri;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">The </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">responsibilities of the Audit Committee are described under the heading &#x201C;Audit Committee Report&#x201D; in this proxy statement</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">.</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Calibri;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-weight:bold;font-size:10pt;">Compensation Committee </font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Calibri;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">All </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">the members of the Corporation&#x2019;s Compensation Committee are independent directors as defined in the Nasdaq Rules.&nbsp;&nbsp;The members of the Compensation Committee are John J. Desmond, Stephen V. Murphy, Milbrey Rennie Taylor, Walter C. Teagle III and Eric J. Tveter.&nbsp;&nbsp;The Committee met seven times during 2019</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">.</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Calibri;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">The </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">Corporation&#x2019;s Board has adopted a formal written charter for the Compensation Committee.&nbsp;&nbsp;A current copy of the charter is available on the Corporation&#x2019;s website by going to </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">www.FNBLI.com</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">, &nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">placing the cursor over &#x201C;Investor Relations,&#x201D; then clicking on &#x201C;Corporate Governance&#x201D; and then clicking on &#x201C;Board Compensation Committee Charter</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">.&#x201D;</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Calibri;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">The </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">purpose of the Compensation Committee is to assist the Board in fulfilling its oversight responsibilities by reviewing and evaluating the Corporation&#x2019;s compensation practices to ensure that appropriate policies, procedures and systems are in place to identify, measure, </font>
		</p>
		<p><font size="1"> </font></p><div style="width:100%">

		<p style="margin:0pt;text-align:center;line-height:100%;font-family:Calibri;font-size: 10pt">

			<font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;"></font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">8</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;"></font>

		</p>

		<p style="margin:0pt;text-align:center;line-height:100%;font-family:Calibri;font-size: 11pt">

			&nbsp;

		</p>

</div><hr size="3" style="color:#999999" width="100%" align="center"></hr><p style="page-break-after:always">&nbsp;</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Calibri;;font-size: 10pt"><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">and control related risks, including strategic, reputation and operational risk.&nbsp;&nbsp;The Committee should identify those employees, including but not limited to the CEO and other executive officers, who could potentially expose the Corporation to material amounts of such risk and arrive at compensation for these employees and non-management directors that is appropriate and competitive and does not expose the Corporation to unacceptable</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">&nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">risk</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">.</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Calibri;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">Among </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">other things, the Compensation Committee is responsible for: (1) implementing and maintaining guiding principles, compensation policies and compensation plans for the CEO, other executive officers and non-management directors, all as set forth in the Corporation&#x2019;s Proxy Statement for its annual meeting of shareholders, and reporting and making recommendations to the Board with respect thereto taking into account market competitive data; (2) recommending to the Board approval of employment agreements for the CEO and other executive officers; (3) evaluating the performance of the CEO against established goals and objectives and approving for Board ratification the base salary level for the CEO subject to any existing employment agreement; (4) reviewing the CEO&#x2019;s performance evaluation</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">s</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;"> of the other executive officers of the Corporation and approving for Board ratification the base salary level of each such officer subject to any existing employment agreements; (5) approving for Board ratification cash incentives and bonuses to be paid to the CEO and other executive officers pursuant to the Corporation&#x2019;s incentive compensation plans or otherwise;&nbsp;&nbsp;(6) setting corporate goals, objectives and compensation plans used to determine cash incentives and bonuses paid to the CEO and other executive officers and equity compensation awarded to the CEO, other executive officers and non-management</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">&nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">directors &#x2013; the Compensation Committee will periodically engage a compensation consulting firm to assist them in this endeavor; (7) approving for Board ratification awards of equity compensation to the CEO, other executive officers and non-management directors pursuant to the Corporation&#x2019;s equity compensation plans or</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">&nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">otherwise; (8) recommending to the Board compensation proposals such as the compensation to be paid to the Corporation&#x2019;s NEOs, say-on-pay, say-when-on-pay or equity incentive plans to be included in the Corporation&#x2019;s annual proxy statement; (9) reviewing the overall annual salary budget for the Bank&#x2019;s entire employee population; (10) conducting, or causing to be conducted, at its discretion, a periodic review of the Corporation&#x2019;s pension, 401(k), and health and welfare plans; (11) reviewing and approving the compensation discussion and analysis included in the Corporation&#x2019;s annual proxy statement and preparing or causing to be prepared the Compensation Committee Report to be included therein; (12) reviewing executive management&#x2019;s determination of compensation of non-executive officers of the Corporation including the total amount of incentive compensation to be paid to such officers; (13) periodically reviewing the incentive compensation plans for senior vice presidents and other employee categories below the level of executive officer; and (14) considering the results of the most recent non-binding, stockholder advisory vote on executive compensation and, if deemed necessary, recommending to the Board changes in compensation policies, practices and decisions</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">.</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Calibri;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">The </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">Compensation Committee administers the Corporation&#x2019;s equity incentive plan, including selecting directors and officers to whom awards are to be made and determining the timing, duration, amount, type and terms of each award.&nbsp;&nbsp;Members of the Compensation Committee as well as all other non-employee directors of the Corporation have been eligible for awards of stock-based compensation in the past and it is currently anticipated that they will be eligible for future awards</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">.</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Calibri;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">In </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">determining an appropriate level of compensation for the CEO, other executive officers and the Board, the Compensation Committee periodically engages an independent compensation consulting firm to gather and help analyze the information necessary to make such determinations.&nbsp;&nbsp;In 2019, the Compensation Committee engaged Pearl Meyer &amp; Partners LLC (&#x201C;</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">Pearl Meyer</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">&#x201D;), an independent national compensation consulting firm, to conduct a review of the compensation of the Company&#x2019;s CEO, other executive officers and the Board.&nbsp;&nbsp;The objective of the review was to provide an assessment of the competitiveness and effectiveness of the Corporation&#x2019;s compensation programs relative to peer banks</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">.</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">&nbsp;</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;text-indent:0pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">In </font><font style="display: inline;">performing their 2019 review, </font><font style="display: inline;">Pearl Meyer </font><font style="display: inline;">worked with the Compensation Committee to develop a custom peer group.&nbsp;&nbsp;The peer banks were similar in size and scope to the Bank, with total assets averaging approximately $4.8 billion.&nbsp;&nbsp;This average compared to total assets for the Bank of approximately $4.1 billion at year-end 2019.&nbsp;&nbsp;The </font><font style="display: inline;">2019 </font><font style="display: inline;">peer group consisted of eighteen (18) publicly-held bank holding companies located in the Bank&#x2019;s general geographic area and included Arrow Financial Corporation, Bridge Bancorp, Inc., Bryn Mawr Bank Corporation, Century Bancorp, Inc., CNB Financial Corporation, ConnectOne Bancorp, Inc., Enterprise Bancorp, Inc., Financial Institutions, Inc., Flushing Financial Corporation, Lakeland Bancorp, Inc., Meridian Bancorp, Inc., Northfield Bancorp, Inc., Oritani Financial Corp., Peapack-Gladstone Financial Corporation, Tompkins Financial Corporation, TrustCo Bank Corp NY, Univest Corporation of Pennsylvania and Washington Trust Bancorp, Inc.&nbsp;&nbsp;In addition to gathering and analyzing compensation data for the peer group, </font><font style="display: inline;">Pearl Meyer </font><font style="display: inline;">also gathered and analyzed peer compensation data from published industry surveys and other proprietary data source.&nbsp;&nbsp;In performing their reviews, </font><font style="display: inline;">Pearl Meyer </font><font style="display: inline;">assessed total remuneration and the individual elements of total remuneration including base salary, annual cash incentive compensation, annual equity awards, retirement benefits and perquisites.&nbsp;&nbsp;Based on their reviews, </font><font style="display: inline;">Pearl Meyer </font><font style="display: inline;">provided the Compensation Committee with a comparison of the compensation of the CEO and other executive officers to the market 10</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:5pt;vertical-align:super;line-height:100%">th</font><font style="display: inline;">, 25</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:5pt;vertical-align:super;line-height:100%">th</font><font style="display: inline;">, 50</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:5pt;vertical-align:super;line-height:100%">th</font><font style="display: inline;">, 75</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:5pt;vertical-align:super;line-height:100%">th </font><font style="display: inline;">and 90</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:5pt;vertical-align:super;line-height:100%">th</font><font style="display: inline;"> percentiles.&nbsp; </font><font style="display: inline;">Pearl Meyer </font><font style="display: inline;">also assessed the elements of Board compensation both individually and in the aggregate, including annual retainers, meeting-based fees and fees for chair roles and special meetings</font><font style="display: inline;">.</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Calibri;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">In </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">addition to the services described above, </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">Pearl Meyer </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">was also engaged in 2019 to perform a review of the long-term incentive plan design of the Corporation&#x2019;s executive incentive plan</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">.</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Calibri;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">&#xFEFF;</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Calibri;font-size: 10pt">

		</p>
		<p><font size="1"> </font></p><div style="width:100%">

		<p style="margin:0pt;text-align:center;line-height:100%;font-family:Calibri;font-size: 10pt">

			<font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;"></font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">9</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;"></font>

		</p>

		<p style="margin:0pt;text-align:center;line-height:100%;font-family:Calibri;font-size: 11pt">

			&nbsp;

		</p>

</div><hr size="3" style="color:#999999" width="100%" align="center"></hr><p style="page-break-after:always">&nbsp;</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Calibri;;font-size: 10pt"><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">The </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">Compensation Committee received a letter from </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">Pearl Meyer </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">regarding its independence under the six factors to be considered for such purposes under Nasdaq Rules, assessed the independence of </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">Pearl Meyer </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">pursuant to such rules and determined that </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">Pearl Meyer </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">is an independent and conflict-free advisor to the Corporation</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">.</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Calibri;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">The </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">Compensation Committee considers the most recent stockholder say-on-pay advisory vote in reviewing the Corporation&#x2019;s executive compensation policies, practices and decisions.&nbsp;&nbsp;The Compensation Committee concluded that no significant revisions were necessary to our executive compensation program as a result of the most recent say-on-pay advisory vote</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">.</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Calibri;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;;font-size: 10pt;font-family:Calibri;text-indent:0pt;margin-left:0pt;padding:0pt 36pt 0pt 0pt;"></font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;"></font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;font-size:10pt;">Compensation Committee Interlocks and Insider Participation.</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;"> &nbsp;No</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">&nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">member of the Compensation Committee: (1) was an officer or employee of the Corporation or the Bank; (2) was formerly an officer of the Corporation or the Bank; or (3) had any relationship requiring disclosure by the Corporation under the SEC&#x2019;s rules governing disclosure of related party transactions.&nbsp; No executive officer of the Corporation served as a director or member of a compensation committee of another entity, one of whose executive officers served as a member of the Corporation&#x2019;s Board or Compensation Committee</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">. &nbsp;</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Calibri;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-weight:bold;font-size:10pt;">Bank Committees: </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-weight:bold;font-size:10pt;">Loan Committee </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-weight:bold;font-size:10pt;">and Asset Liability Committee</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-weight:bold;font-size:10pt;">&nbsp;</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Calibri;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">The </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">Loan Committee is responsible for providing oversight with respect to the Bank&#x2019;s lending activities.</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;"> &nbsp; &nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">The Asset Liability Committee is responsible for providing oversight with respect to the Bank&#x2019;s achievement of its overall objective of optimizing returns consistent with prudent risk management regarding assets, liabilities, equity and off-balance sheet activities</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">.</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:center;font-family:Calibri;font-size: 10pt">
			<a name="BoardMemberAttendance"></a><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-weight:bold;font-size:10pt;">BOARD MEMBER ATTENDANCE AT ANNUAL MEETINGS</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Calibri;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">The </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">Board strongly encourages each of its members to attend the Annual Meeting of Stockholders.&nbsp;&nbsp;In this regard, the Board sets the date for the Annual Meeting of Stockholders to coincide with its April Board meeting.&nbsp;&nbsp;All directors attended the prior year&#x2019;s Annual Meeting of Stockholders which was held on April 16, 2019</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">.</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:center;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Calibri;font-size: 10pt">
			<a name="SecurityHolderCommunications"></a><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-weight:bold;font-size:10pt;">SECURITY</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-weight:bold;font-size:10pt;">&nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-weight:bold;font-size:10pt;">HOLDER COMMUNICATIONS TO THE BOARD OF DIRECTORS</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Calibri;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">The </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">Corporation&#x2019;s Board does not have a formal process for security holders to send communications to the Board.&nbsp;&nbsp;The Board believes that a formal process is unnecessary because the Corporation is relatively small and both the Chairman of the Board and the CEO, who is also a director, are easily accessible by telephone and mail</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">.</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:center;font-family:Calibri;font-size: 10pt">
			<a name="CompensationofDirectors"></a><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-weight:bold;font-size:10pt;">COMPENSATION OF DIRECTORS</font>
